barometer -the barometer shewed less atmospheric disturbance for this month than for any corresponding one for some years past, notwithstanding the violent gale which raged during the night of the 4th. the lowest reading (29.322 in.) took place on the last named day, and its highest (30.267 in) on the 26th. the difference between the highest and the lowest readings was 0.945 inches, while in 1868 it was 1.113, and the average is 1.13 inch. the greatest mean difference between two following days (24th and 26th) was 0.477 in, and the least 0.026 [inches], the mean for the month being 0.204 in. the latter in 1868 was 0.241 [inches], and the mean is 0.219 in.   the following are the means of the usual tri-daily readings: - 1869 [in inches]: 8am: 29.895 2pm: 29.866 10pm: 29.873 means: 29.878 --- 1868 [in inches]: 8am: 30.103 2pm: 30.067 10pm: 30.084 means: 30.085  avg. 9 years, 29.947 inches.

temperature - though the early part of october brought one of the most destructive gales that ever devastated this province, and the weather prophets would have it that this was but the beginning of grand series of such disasters, happily it turned out otherwise; and so far from the remainder of the month being blustering or unpleasant, it was one of the quietest and finest and warmest known for many years. the temperature of the three first weeks meaned 7.81° above that of the corresponding ones in 1868, and 3.64° above the average for those weeks. a cold spell, however, came with the fourth, and its mean fell 6.81° below the temperature of the same week last year, and 9° below the average since 1860. the several periodic means deduced from bi-daily readings were as follows for this and former years:- --- 1869. [in degrees] 1st week: 54.56 2nd week: 50.19 3rd week: 46.81 4th week: 36.56 --- 1868. [in degrees] 1st week: 48.17 2nd week: 47.00 3rd week: 35.46 4th week: 37.38 --- avg. 9 years. [in degrees] 1st week: 50.00 2nd week: 47.42 3rd week: 45.23 4th week: 39.50 --- an inspection of the above figures shews that although october had many pleasant characteristics  yet its temperature was somewhat abnormal  in extremes of heat and cold; for while the difference between the means of the first and last weeks was 25° the average is only 0.5° the highest heat  recorded during this month was 70° on the 4th. this is 6° above the highest recorded since 1860, but the notes left by the late mr. gove show a maximum of 76° in 1851. the minimum of last year was 59° and the average of 9 years is 61.77° the lowest temperature observed for the month was 23[°] on the 28th, which is exactly the figure reached in 1868, but 3° below the average minimum. the extreme range for the month was the very unusual one for st. john of 47°, or 11° more than in 1868, and the same above the average monthly disturbance; yet the greatest change in one day was only 20°, and the mean of daily disturbance 9.52° or nearly one degree less than the average, and 2.16° less than for october last year. the warmest day (4th) had a mean heat of 64°, and the coldest (28th) of 28°, the former being 7.3° above the warmest day for the same period in 1868, and the latter one degree lower than the lowest mean last year.  the usual hourly readings gave the following results for the month as a whole: --- 1869. [in degrees] 6am: 43.74 10am: 49.45 2pm: 51.13 6pm: 48.45 10pm: 45.03 mean (6am, 2pm, and 10pm): 46.63 --- 1868. [in degrees] 6am: 37.51 10am: 43.71 2pm: 46.71 6pm: 44.20 10pm: 41.48 mean (6am, 2pm, and 10pm): 41.90 --- avg. 9 years. [in degrees] 6am: 41.71 10am: 47.10 2pm: 49.96 6pm: 46.98 10pm: 44.17 mean (6am, 2pm, and 10pm): 45.28

auroral vapour from about 8 pm. 12 pm aurora has taken a more definite form and is now rising in flat broken, greyish streams from north west to north east without black cloud. converging and forming a corona over zenith. night still warm and clear.

sharp peal of thunder, followed about 5 minutes afterwards by a few heavy drops of rain. sun shining all the time but sky became clouded soon after (10 pm) sky is partly clouded, but sufficiently clear to exhibit a very fine aurora, which though not very brilliant covers the greater part of sky and forms a good corona (11 pm) aurora still visible; diffused and motionless. frequent flashes of lightning along; northern horizons. aurora disappeared a little before (12 pm) and fog set in. lightning increased after midnight and was, sometimes, very bright. thunder heard about 1:30 am
aurora visible in north and north east. no black cloud rises about 30 degrees to 40 degrees above horizon in flat shooting streams of bluish light faintly tinged with red
aurora from 8 o clock, but not extensive, being only confined to the north and reaching up but a short distance

aurora from about 9 oclock; not any extensive, but forming an arch across the northern horizon; but at 10:25 o clock pale cold looking streamers extended to the zenith, covering the northern hemisphere of the sky (12pm) aurora continues flowing in bright but broken currents from northern horizon to zenith. ray near the north western and north eastern extremities occassionally tinted red. night still
first ice of season. auroral vapour shining from behind thin vapory clouds
aurora at 8 o clock in beams
aurora (12 pm) from about 7 o clock; clear bright arch
aurora: in alternated needle like forms rising in the north quiet and widly apart surrounded by a luminous haze of reddish hue
aurora in steady diffused light visible since sunset, surmounting an irregular arch of greyish black cloud

raining all morning sky lighted up a little at 8:30am but soon darkened again. ([at] 2pm) has rained steadily all forenoon: wind backed to se about noon: blowing fresh and gusty. ([at] 6pm) has rained heavily all afternoon and still continues. ([at] 8pm) rain continues in unabated volume. very dark wind increasing and veering southward. ([at] 10pm) fierce wild wind blowing from aboutssw in long gusty waves. still dark; but clouds less dense than during the earlier part of the evening. no rain since about 8:30 o'clock

light rain between 7 and 8 but rain of last night ended shortly after midnight. there has been, however, a few scuds since. wind continues very high. ([at] 2pm) wind westerly all forenoon very high and squally with occasional glimpses or bursts of sunshine: overcast at present. ([at] 6pm) the storm has been gradually abating all afternoon, the clouds lightning and the wind becoming less violent, while the barometer has been rising steadily. ([at] 10pm) the sky is now cloudlessand the wind much easier than it was in the afternoon, though it is still blowing strongly. this has had the effect of drying up the ground to a great extent after the heavy rain which preceded it.
atmosphere very smokey from about 6pm untill about 9pm. first seen advancing from westward about 4 o'clock [4pm]

([at] 9am) overcast. ([at] 2pm) snowing since noon. ([at] 6pm) snowed constantly until about 5:30pm. ([at] 10pm) after whichthere was a lull, until about 7 o'clock [7pm] when rain began to fall and continued in heavy showers until about 5am of 30th [nov]

wind veered by east and south [se?] to sw  during the night (of 29th) and blew for a while with great fury. reached its maximum between 5 and 6 o'clock [5-6am]. several vessels stranded in courtenay bay. two wrecked on foul ground. 5 out of 7 of a crew belonging to the "reward" of nova scotia drowned. side walls of young mens christian association building blown down. temperature rose during the earlier part of the storm (while the rain fell) 23 degrees or from 20 [degrees] to 43 degrees. when wind got to westward began to fall again. barometer reached its minimum 29.100 [inches] about 8 o'clock: having fallen 1 inch in 34 hours
light spears of aurora visible between 8 and 9 oclock and later in night
the last week in this month was the coldest in 12 years
brilliant aurora, sometimes covers whole sky; displaying deep red, blue and purple tints

storm: storm of wind and snow, from ne during the night. depth of snow about 2 inches. great velocity of wind: 19 miles per hour. heaviest between 7pm and mighnight. barometer began to fall morning of 2nd and continued until 12pm of 3rd [march], when it marked 28.97 inch. whole fall of 0.966 inches

storm: storm of wind and snow. began about 2pm and continued until about 10pm. snow fall 12 inches. wind ne while storm was heaviest. changed through n to nw about 8pm. greatest noted velocity 16 miles per hour; but came at times in strong swelling gusts that doubtless succeeded this considerably. barometer - began to fall from 29.69in about 8am of 10th and continued until 8pm: whole fall 0.233in in 12 hours. rose rapidly afterwards. increase in 12 hours 0.623 inches.

storm: storm of wind, hail and snow. wind se when storm began (8pm) but shifted about 1am of 12th to sw. greatest velocity (9pm to 10pm) 17 miles per hour. hail and snow from 9-11pm. depth 1 inch only. barometer at 8am 11th stood at 29.98 inch, fell slowly during foremorn and more rapidly as storm approached. whole fall (8am until midnight) 0.417: 0.25in of which took place in 3.5 hours - during time of storm

storm: wind and snow. snow began to fall 10:15pm and continued all night. drifted greatly. wind shifted from ne to east about 9am of 20th. remained light and steady all day. began to quicken about 10pm. blew heavily from about 12pm (20th) until 9am of 21st. heaviest from 4[am] to 6am. abated as the day advanced and at 4pm was quite calm. began to freshen again about 7pm (21st) and move by s to sw. remained sw about 24 hours and then veered westward. barometer at 2pm of 20th marked 30.012 inch, and from this continued to fall until about 4pm of 21st, when it stood at 29.142inches. whole fall in 20 hours 0.87inches. recovered slightly during the evening but declined again during the night and marked at 8am of 22nd 29.136in. weather remained unsettled until about noon of the 22nd. total snowfall, 8.05inches
aurora borealis: visible about 11pm, formed by rugged broken patches of light ascending from behind an irregular black cloud that extended about 60 degrees from the horizon

storm of wind and rain. began about 7:45pm when rain began to fall and wind to freshen. moderate greater part of time. wind heaviest from 12pm 29th until about 4pm 30th. average velocity for this period 18 miles per hour. rained--but not continually--from 7:45pm 29th until about 6pm 30th. heaviest between 12pm 29th and 2am 30th. whole fall 0.53inch.
narrow strip of auroral arch extended through zenith, from n. western horizon to s eastern
narrow strip of auroral arch extended through zenith, from n. western horizon to s eastern
heavy gale all day. wind north to north east. greatest velocity about 26 miles per hour between 7 and 8 o'clock pm.
